# Merge the two datasets by performing a left join with the "randomizedDataset" as the dominant dataset and the "BrakeTime" dataset. Create a new dataset called "dfc" and use the common primary key (PK) "id" to match and add the "time" variable from the "BrakeTime" dataset to the corresponding records in the "randomizedDataset".

dfc<-randomizedData %>%

B. Provide analyses that investigates the relationship between alcohol dose level and response time. Provide any graphs/outputs and interpretation of the graphs/outputs needed to assess the assumptions required for your analysis. If you decide to transform the data, provide justification for the decision.

#Since the outcome variable is continuous and there are no confounding factors requiring adjustment at this stage, an ANOVA analysis can be conducted.

# perform ANOVA
fit <- aov(TIME ~ DOSE, data = dfc)

# summarize results
summary(fit)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## DOSE          2  302.8  151.38   20.43 1.04e-08 ***
## Residuals   177 1311.4    7.41                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1


Answer:The table presents the results of the analysis for the variables “TIME” and “GENDER” in relation to different dose levels.Among total 180 participants,significant differences were observed for “TIME” across the dose levels (p < 0.001), with increasing means observed as the dose level increased. No significant differences were found for “GENDER” across the dose levels. The ANOVA analysis was performed to examine the impact of the variable “DOSE” on the response variable. The data consisted of 2 degrees of freedom for the “DOSE” factor and 177 degrees of freedom for the residuals. The analysis revealed a significant effect of “DOSE” on the response variable, as indicated by a high F value of 20.43 (p < 0.001). The sum of squares for the “DOSE” factor was 302.8, with a mean square of 151.38. The remaining variability in the data was captured by the residuals, with a sum of squares of 1311.4 and a mean square of 7.41. These results strongly support the conclusion that the variable “DOSE” has a significant impact on the response variable.

Based on the plot, there are clear distinctions in time responses between males and females, particularly in the high dose group. To delve deeper into this relationship, a linear regression model was built, revealing that the varying doses significantly impacted time after accounting for gender. Moreover, the model highlighted the noteworthy influence of gender on the outcome, with males demonstrating shorter time responses compared to females.

D. Provide a paragraph that details your findings regarding the relationship between response time, gender and alcohol dose.

The linear regression model shows that the intercept value is statistically significant at p < 0.0001, indicating a significant effect of the constant term on the dependent variable: Time. The variable GENDERMALE is also significant at p < 0.001, suggesting that being male is associated with a decrease in the Time. Additionally, the two dose variables, DOSE0.25 CC/LB and DOSE0.50 CC/LB, are both significant at p < 0.05 and p < 0.001, respectively, indicating that higher doses are associated with an increase in the time. Overall, these results suggest that the gender of the subject and the dose of the medication are significant predictors of time. However, the limitation is that R squared value in this model is only 0.22, indicating that only 22% of the variation in the dependent variable was explained by the variables in this model. Therefore, to improve the model’s performance, more potential confounding variables should be included.

         num=as.factor(num))

1. Please create the wide-format dataset (postprocesseduids.csv) as described above, using a program of your choice (i.e., R, SAS, STATA, or PYTHON)?

wide_data <- dfq2 %>%
  mutate(num = as.numeric(num)) %>%
  group_by(ptid, type) %>%
  mutate(svol = sum(volume)) %>%
  mutate(snum = n(),
         totyn=type)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(ptid) %>%
  mutate(totvolusvol = sum(volume),
         totvolusyn = factor(ifelse(is.na(type), 0, 1))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-c("num","time","volume"))%>%
  group_by(ptid, type) %>%
  distinct(svol,.keep_all = T) %>% #To solve "not unique identified value" for svol, snum in the pivot_wider process
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = "type",
    names_prefix = "type_",
    names_sep = "_",
    values_from = c("svol","snum","totyn")
  )%>%
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(totnum=sum(snum_type_0,snum_type_1,snum_type_2,snum_type_NA, na.rm = TRUE), #get total number of flu shot received. 
        totyn_type_NA =ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_NA),0, 1),
        totyn_type_0 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_0),0, 1),
        totyn_type_1 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_1),0, 1),
        totyn_type_2 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_2),0, 1)) %>%
  select(ptid, 
         totbol0yn=totyn_type_0, totbol2yn=totyn_type_2, totbol1yn=totyn_type_1, 
         totbol0num=snum_type_0, totbol2num=snum_type_2, totbol1num=snum_type_1,
         totbo0vol=svol_type_0, totbo2vol=svol_type_2, totbo1vol=svol_type_1,
         totbolusnum=totnum,
         totbolusyn=totvolusyn,
         totbolusvol=totvolusvol
         )%>% #rename and reorder the dataset to align with the example dataset.remove the xxx_NA if the whole column does not have any value. 
  filter(ptid!=30089)#remove the outlier: ptid=30089 does not receive any type of flu shot but got the total volume input based on the wide dataset example. 


#Export dataset
rio::export(wide_data,"wide_data.csv")

From this summary, we can see that there is one missing value in the “type” variable.The “num” variable seems to represent time to get vaccination, which should be 1-5, but here there are 5 other values as outliers.The “type” variable appears to be a categorical variable with three categories: 0, 1, and 2. There are 378 observations with type 0, 2 observations with type 1, and 202 observations with type 2.The “time” variable seems to have two categories, 0 and 1, with 127 observations for time 0 and 455 observations for time 1.The “volume” variable appears to be a numerical variable with a minimum of 4, maximum of 999, and a mean of 483.8.It’s difficult to determine if there are any abnormalities in the data without additional information, but it seems like there are no major outliers or unusual values in the dataset.From the summary we can also tell that there are 1 missing value from variable num, type and time respectively.

# --------------------------Copy from previous chunk for Rmarkdown to successfully Knit.------------------
wide_data <- dfq2 %>%
  mutate(num = as.numeric(num)) %>%
  group_by(ptid, type) %>%
  mutate(svol = sum(volume)) %>%
  mutate(snum = max(num), 
         totyn=type)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(ptid) %>%
  mutate(totvolusvol = sum(volume),
         totvolusyn = factor(ifelse(is.na(type), 0, 1))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-c("num","time","volume"))%>%
  group_by(ptid, type) %>%
  distinct(svol,.keep_all = T) %>% #To solve "not unique identified value" for svol, snum in the pivot_wider process
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = "type",
    names_prefix = "type_",
    names_sep = "_",
    values_from = c("svol","snum","totyn")
  )%>%
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(totnum=sum(snum_type_0,snum_type_1,snum_type_2,snum_type_NA, na.rm = TRUE), #get total number of flu shot received. 
        totyn_type_NA =ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_NA),0, 1),
        totyn_type_0 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_0),0, 1),
        totyn_type_1 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_1),0, 1),
        totyn_type_2 = ifelse(is.na(totyn_type_2),0, 1)) %>%
  select(ptid, 
         totbol0yn=totyn_type_0, totbol2yn=totyn_type_2, totbol1yn=totyn_type_1, 
         totbol0num=snum_type_0, totbol2num=snum_type_2, totbol1num=snum_type_1,
         totbo0vol=svol_type_0, totbo2vol=svol_type_2, totbo1vol=svol_type_1,
         totbolusnum=totnum,
         totbolusyn=totvolusyn,
         totbolusvol=totvolusvol
         )%>% #rename and reorder the dataset to align with the example dataset.

         totbol1yn=factor(totbol1yn),

#Check outliers by using visualized plots based on the format of var

for (i in colnames(wd)) {
  if (is.numeric(wd[[i]])) {
    hist(wd[[i]], main = paste("Histogram of", i), xlab = i)
  } else if (is.character(wd[[i]])) {
    barplot(table(wd[[i]]), main = paste("Barplot of", i), xlab = i)
  } else if (is.factor(wd[[i]])) {
    barplot(table(wd[[i]]), main = paste("Barplot of", i), xlab = i)
    tbl <- table(wd[[i]], useNA = "ifany")
    print(kbl(tbl, caption = str_c("Table of"," ", i )))
  }
}

#Further check factor variables for distribution and outliers
for (i in colnames(wd)) {
  if (is.factor(wd[[i]]) && length(levels(wd[[i]])) >1 && length(levels(wd[[i]])) <= 2) {
    p <- ggplot(data = wd, aes_string(x = i, y = "totbolusvol")) +
      geom_violin(trim = FALSE, na.rm = TRUE) +
      geom_boxplot(width = 0.1,  na.rm = TRUE) +
      theme_classic()
    print(p)
  }
  else if (is.factor(wd[[i]]) && length(levels(wd[[i]])) > 2) {
    p2 <- ggplot(data = wd, aes_string(x = i, y = "totbolusvol")) +
      geom_violin(aes(fill = .data[[i]]), trim = FALSE, na.rm = TRUE) +
      geom_boxplot(width = 0.1, fill = "white", color = "black",  na.rm = TRUE) +
      theme_classic()
    print(p2)
  }
}

#checking by z-score: volume
z_scores_df <- as_tibble(scale(wide_data$totbolusvol))
ggplot(z_scores_df, aes(x = V1)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "steelblue", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Z Scores", x = "Z Score", y = "Count")

Conclusion: The wide-format dataset exhibits similar outliers compared to the original dataset. The combination of barplots embedded within the violin plots helps identify suspicious values that fall outside the 75th percentile quartile range and highlights the distribution differences among groups. Notable outliers include: 1) The “type” variable for each flu shot having values over 5, which should be considered outliers since the codebook specifies a range of 1-5. 2) The “ptid” with ID 30089 shows no flu shot record but has a total volume entry, suggesting a potential input typo. 3) For the potential outcome variable, total volume, applying a Z-score threshold of \(\pm\) 3 reveals a reduced number of values beyond the boundaries, indicating possible outliers. Moreover, it is crucial to exercise caution regarding the presence of numerous NA values across different variables.
